{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:33:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16398"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.02,0.03,0.78,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2349"},{"type":"tags","id":"4043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4220"},{"type":"tags","id":"4550"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43629"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of urinary incontinence. She reports leaking urine when coughing or lifting heavy objects, as well as experiencing sudden urges to void with occasional leakage before reaching the toilet. She has had three vaginal deliveries, the last being 25 years ago. Her medical history includes hypertension and obesity with a BMI of 32 kg/m2. Her only medication is amlodipine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals anterior vaginal wall prolapse. Urodynamic studies demonstrate detrusor overactivity during bladder filling and urethral hypermobility with increased vesical pressure during cough stress test.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stress urinary incontinence","Functional incontinence","Urge urinary incontinence","Mixed urinary incontinence","Overflow incontinence"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and urodynamic findings consistent with mixed urinary incontinence. The history reveals both stress incontinence symptoms (leakage with coughing and lifting) and urge incontinence symptoms (sudden urges with leakage). This is supported by urodynamic findings showing both detrusor overactivity and urethral hypermobility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed urinary incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as the combination of both stress and urge incontinence symptoms. Risk factors include age, vaginal deliveries, obesity, and anterior vaginal wall prolapse, all of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress urinary incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E alone would present with leakage only during increased intra-abdominal pressure (coughing, lifting, exercise) without the urge component. While urethral hypermobility is present, this doesn\u0027t explain all of the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrge urinary incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E alone would present with sudden, compelling desires to void with associated leakage, but without the stress-related symptoms. While detrusor overactivity is present on urodynamics, this doesn\u0027t explain the stress-related leakage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverflow incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with frequent small volume voids and constant dribbling, often due to bladder outlet obstruction or neurogenic bladder. This pattern is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctional incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when physical, cognitive or environmental barriers prevent timely toileting. There is no evidence of such barriers in this otherwise well patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of mixed incontinence typically begins with conservative measures including pelvic floor exercises, bladder training, and lifestyle modifications. Medical therapy often includes both anticholinergic medications for the urge component and potentially surgical intervention for the stress component if conservative measures fail.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mixed urinary incontinence presents with symptoms of both stress and urge incontinence.","Urodynamic studies can demonstrate both detrusor overactivity and urethral hypermobility in mixed incontinence.","A thorough history should include triggers, timing, and impact on quality of life for urinary symptoms."],"references":["Royal Australian College of General Practitioners (RACGP). Urinary incontinence [Internet]. East Melbourne: RACGP; [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/silver-book/part-a/urinary-incontinence","Jha S, Jeppson PC, Dokmeci F, Marquini GV, Sartori MGF, Moalli P, Malik SA. Management of mixed urinary incontinence: IUGA committee opinion. Int Urogynecol J. 2024 Feb;35(2):291-301. doi: 10.1007/s00192-023-05694-z. Epub 2024 Jan 22. PMID: 38252279; PMCID: PMC10908639."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T12:15:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T12:16:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9089"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65017"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","positi